# Automated Backup Scripts

## Project Objective
To write a script that automatically copies critical files from a source folder to a destination foler(like an external hard drive) 
 on a regular schedule, while keeping a log of activities.

## What you will need 
 Your Computer: Any Operating System Windows, MacOS and Linux
 Code Editor: Visual Studio Code or Notepad or Nano Editor
 A Scripting Language: For Windows - Powershell
                       For MacOS/Linux - Bash
 A Task Scheduler: Windows Task Scheduler or cron for linux

## FOLLOW THE SEQUENCE
Phase 1: Set up your Test Folders
         - Create a folder on your desktop called Source_Data and put a few files and images into it.
         - Now create an another folder called Backup_Destination on different drive (USB Drive) or else where on your computer

Phase 2: Write the Backup Script
         - Write a small script telling the computer exactly what to move.
          A basic powershell script
          
# Basic Backup Script using Robocopy
$source = "C:\Users\YourName\Desktop\Source_Data"
$destination = "E:\Backup_Destination"
$logFile = "C:\Users\YourName\Desktop\Backup_Log.txt"

# /MIR mirrors the directory (deletes files in destination if deleted in source)
# /LOG tells it where to save the text record of the backup
robocopy $source $destination /MIR /LOG:$logFile

 Save this file as DailyBackup.ps1 for Poweshell

 Phase 3: Automation
          - Open the Task Scheduler App in Windows
          - Click create Basic Task and name it "Daily Data Backup"
          - Set the trigger to daily and set the time ( eg.02:00am)
          - Start a program, type powershell.exe, and in the "Add arguments" box type the path to your script C:\Path\To\DailyBackup.ps1").

Phase 4: Verification and Logging
         - Manually run the task to test it.
         - Check your Backup Destination folder to ensure files are copied successfully.
         - Then, open your Backup_Log.txt file.

Hence, this is how the daily backup system for automation works









































